<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="un1013p"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="un1" href="#un1013">UN1: </a>  <a href="../../FF/unbs/un1all.htm#un1013p"> (NLI.3) 13(p)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 3 modes of matter Prakriti, / Tamos (dark), rajas (activity) &amp; sattva (light).</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Kapila&apos;s system is obviously dualistic, as he recognises two principles: Pur&#363;sha, the Soul, or the Self, and Prakriti or Nature. The latter consists of <mark>three modes of matter</mark>: Sattva, Rajas and Tamas. <mark>Tamas represents what is fixed and stable or &ldquo;dark&rdquo;; Rajas the element of activity; and Sattva the manifestation of rhythm or &ldquo;light.&rdquo;</mark> In every man also these three modes of matter are found. <small> <a name="THRdec1908" href="/udra/udex.htm#THRdec1908"><cite title="source">The Theosophical Review</cite></a> (December 1908), Hedwig S. Albarus, &ldquo;Modern Idealism and the Ved&amacr;ntic Philosophy&rdquo; 351</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c07256b" href="../../../F/FF/fnbs/c07all.htm#c07256b">VI.C.07:256(b)</a>, <a name="c07256c" href="../../../F/FF/fnbs/c07all.htm#c07256c">VI.C.07:256(c)</a> </dd> </dd></dl>
